"The travelling public gained enormously by the change. It gained, for example, in time, for the round of the Inner Circle was completed in 50 instead of 70 minutes. It also gained immeasurably in comfort through the purging of the tunnels of the sulphurous fumes which, however wholesome they might be, were certainly not palatable, and by the removal of the grimy deposits which hung thick upon the walls. The old rolling stock, with its narrow cramped compartments, gave way to long and brilliantly lighted corridor coaches, and the general impression of the Londoner was that he had come into possession of a brand new Metropolitan."